1. PENDING
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → not enough CPU or memory on nodes
  → too many pods on node (instance limit)
  → no nodes match the node selector
  → PVC not bound (storage not ready)
  → taint on node, pod has no toleration

Check:
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
  kubectl get nodes
  kubectl get events -n <namespace>

Fix:
  → add more nodes or increase node size
  → fix resource requests/limits
  → fix node selector or tolerations
  → fix PVC / storage class


2. CRASHLOOPBACKOFF
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → application crashes on startup
  → wrong command or entrypoint in dockerfile
  → missing environment variables
  → missing config files or secrets
  → app cannot connect to database
  → out of memory (OOMKilled then restarts)

Check:
  kubectl logs <pod-name>
  kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

Fix:
  → check application logs for error
  → fix entrypoint / command in deployment
  → add missing env vars or secrets
  → fix database connection string
  → increase memory limit


3. OOMKILLED (Out of Memory Killed)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → pod used more memory than its limit
  → memory leak in application
  → limit set too low

Check:
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
  look for: "OOMKilled" in Last State

Fix:
  → increase memory limit in deployment
  → fix memory leak in application

  resources:
    limits:
      memory: "512Mi"    ← increase this
    requests:
      memory: "256Mi"


4. IMAGEPULLBACKOFF / ERRIMAGEPULL
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → wrong image name or tag
  → image does not exist in registry
  → private registry needs credentials
  → no internet access on node

Check:
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
  look for: "Failed to pull image"

Fix:
  → fix image name and tag in deployment
  → create imagePullSecret for private registry
  → verify image exists in registry

  kubectl create secret docker-registry regcred \
    --docker-server=<registry> \
    --docker-username=<user> \
    --docker-password=<pass>


5. RUNCONTAINERERROR
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → container cannot start at all
  → wrong entrypoint or command
  → volume mount path does not exist
  → config map or secret not found
  → permission denied on mounted volume

Check:
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
  kubectl get events -n <namespace>

Fix:
  → fix command/entrypoint in yaml
  → fix volume mount paths
  → create missing configmap or secret
  → fix file permissions on volume


6. ERROR
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → container exited with non-zero code
  → application threw unhandled exception
  → script inside container failed

Check:
  kubectl logs <pod-name>
  kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous

Fix:
  → check exit code in describe output
  → fix application error


7. TERMINATING (stuck)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → pod stuck in terminating state
  → finalizer blocking deletion
  → node is unreachable

Check:
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
  kubectl get nodes

Fix:
  → force delete the pod
  kubectl delete pod <pod-name> --force --grace-period=0


8. CONTAINERCREATING (stuck)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → volume not attached yet
  → image still being pulled
  → configmap or secret missing
  → network plugin issue (CNI)

Check:
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
  kubectl get events -n <namespace>

Fix:
  → wait for volume to attach
  → create missing configmap/secret
  → check CNI plugin is running
  kubectl get pods -n kube-system


9. UNSCHEDULABLE
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → no node has enough resources
  → node selector does not match any node
  → pod has taint that no node tolerates
  → affinity rules cannot be satisfied

Check:
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
  look for: "0/3 nodes are available"

Fix:
  → scale up node group
  → fix node selector labels
  → add tolerations to pod spec
  → relax affinity rules


10. EVICTED
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Reason:
  → node ran out of disk space
  → node ran out of memory
  → kubelet evicted pod to free resources

Check:
  kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
  kubectl describe node <node-name>

Fix:
  → clean up disk on node
  → add more nodes
  → set proper resource requests
  → add PodDisruptionBudget


QUICK REFERENCE
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Error                  First Command to Run
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Pending              → kubectl describe pod <pod>
CrashLoopBackOff     → kubectl logs <pod> --previous
OOMKilled            → kubectl describe pod <pod>
ImagePullBackOff     → kubectl describe pod <pod>
RunContainerError    → kubectl describe pod <pod>
Terminating stuck    → kubectl delete pod --force
ContainerCreating    → kubectl get events -n <ns>
Unschedulable        → kubectl describe pod <pod>
Evicted              → kubectl describe node <node>


INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

"For any pod error my first two commands are
 always kubectl describe pod and kubectl logs.
 describe shows scheduling and event errors,
 logs shows application errors. Between these
 two commands I can solve 90% of pod issues." ✅
